author: Inside Edition
description: The series "Monster: The Ed Gein Story" has become a massive hit on Netflix. Ed Gein and his unspeakable crimes were the inspiration for several horror movie classics like "Psycho," "The Texas Chainsaw Massacre," and "The Silence of the Lambs." The Monster" series is from producer Ryan Murphy, who’s already tackled the Menendez Brothers and serial killer Jeffrey Dahmer. Gein killed at least two women and robbed the graves of freshly buried people to steal body parts for his collection.
title: 'Monster: The Ed Gein Story' Becomes Massive Hit On Netflix

author: Inside Edition
description: The “Warheads Challenge" is all over social media. A Warhead is an extremely sour candy, and the challenge involves popping one into your mouth and waiting to see who makes a sour face first. Ten-year-old Leah and her 7-year-old brother, Logan, popped the candies and started bouncing on a trampoline. The candy lodged in Logan's throat and he started choking. Leah sprang into action and performed the Heimlich maneuver. In an instant, Logan coughed up the candy. They spoke with Inside Edition.
title: 10-Year-Old Girl Saves 7-Year-Old Brother Choking on Candy

author: Inside Edition
description: Kristen Hogan is accused of poisoning her ex-boyfriend with anti-freeze. Police say the 34-year-old victim drank a small amount of wine from his refrigerator. He was rushed to the hospital and a lab test later determined the wine contained anti-freeze. Hogan was arrested and cops say she told them she “never intended to kill him, but just wanted to make him sick as payback for him being mentally abusive." Kristen Hogan's lawyer says she plans on pleading not guilty.
title: Woman Accused Of Poisoning Ex-Boyfriend Appears in Court

author: Inside Edition
description: A family had just moved into a new house outside Seattle. They were in the garage and their 3-year-old son was playing on the front lawn when he found what he thought was a toy, but it was actually a live grenade. Inside Edition's Jim Moret spoke to shocked parents Zane and Amanda Gilbert. Their son, Daymon, is alive and well. It could have ended in disaster. Two weeks ago, Inside Edition spoke to the grieving parents of a 12-year-old son who was killed when a grenade exploded in his bedroom.
title: 3-Year-Old Walks Into House Carrying Live Grenade

author: Inside Edition
description: Federal authorities say an #Uberdriver started one of the most devastating fires in #LosAngeles history: The Palisades Fire.
title: Did Uber Driver Start Devastating Palisades Fire? #shorts

author: Inside Edition
description: With Halloween approaching, Erebus Haunted Attraction is getting ready for its 25th year of scaring the daylights out of guests in Michigan. In order to do that, they have to train a whole new crop of vampires, zombies, ghosts and other unnerving beings. The actors say scaring someone is not as easy as it sounds. The Attraction is open daily until November 2nd. Inside Edition Digital’s Mara Montalbano has more.
title: 'Scare School' Teaches Monsters How To Terrify Guests

author: Inside Edition
description: Zach Bryan only released a snippet of the song titled “Bad News,” but it was enough to spark an outcry from #MAGA world.
title: Zach Bryan Angers MAGA With ICE Lyrics #shorts

author: Inside Edition
description: It was an unscheduled stop on this bus route, but a necessary one. Driver Barbara Baker spotted a child walking alone down a street in Tampa, Florida, and knew she couldn't just keep driving. Baker says the child seemed physically fine, but was obviously lost. Inside Edition Digital’s Mara Montalbano has more.
title: Bus Driver Stops Mid-Route To Help Lost Child Walking Alone On Tampa Street

author: Inside Edition
description: Country music icon #DollyParton posted a video on social media Wednesday, a day after her sister made a post pleading for prayers.
title: Dolly Parton: 'I Ain't Dead Yet!'

author: Inside Edition
description: A deputy ran to save a little girl from a lake, but someone beat him to it: her big brother. The Pasco Sheriff's Office in Florida says the original 911 call was for a missing autistic child. By the time the deputy arrived, the child was found, but not exactly safe. The good thing is that the 5-year-old wasn't alone. Inside Edition Digital’s Mara Montalbano has more.
title: Brother Saves Nonverbal Little Sister From Lake In Florida
